They recently opened their store location earlier this month and the word is now out!!  People are lining up out the door for their most tasty and juicy hot chicken.  The menu is still the same with the basic tenders or sliders however, the coleslaw is not part of the plate anymore..it's part of their sides.  Along with the coleslaw being a side they have added macaroni and cheese to the mix.  There is also a new spice level of reaper and x-hot you might want to try if you are brave enough.  They serve drinks and alcohol as well!  Additionally, because they have upgraded from the OG parking lot location there is limited parking in the parking lot and credit cards are now accepted.  The few times I have been here there has been a wait of an hour in line and the your food is served shortly after.

Mama Rao's is the kind of place to get a wonderful dining experience,  not just a meal. The warm greeting you get at the door, usually by the owner, is echoed by the wait staff, setting up an inviting atmosphere.  The restaurant itself is tastefully designed and often serves as party room for private and corporate functions. I have eaten intimate meals with my wife, shared  fun dinners with groups, and attended holiday parties and other functions here with consistent  satisfaction every time. And I haven't even gotten to the FOOD! Well, this is a family restaurant.  You can tell how much care goes into every plate that leaves the kitchen. They change up the menu to keep things interesting,  but you can signature items pretty regularly.  In addition,  you won't leave without a signature Lemon Drop cookie. I never thought I'd like them,  being a strictly chocolate-based dessert fan, but one bite changed all that! I try not to write negative reviews whenever possible,  an with places like Mama Rao's,  it is very easy to stay positive.  Mangia!!

NEVER AGAIN. Went there the other day. I ordered a pappardelle dish and asked for them to leave the tomato sauce out bc the  menu said it was a white wine sauce topped with a little marinara. They  served me pieces of cut up lasagna (Guess they don't think people actually know what pappardelle look like ) floating in a disgusting opaque water.  It looked liked someone's leftover soup. On top of that it had some sort of dairy in it after I told the waiter I was allergic. Anyway,  this soupy mess was completely inedible so the server asked to change it. WELL, THE OWNER/MANAGER told him not to change it claiming it didn't have any dairy and that he was sure because he had made it himself. REALLY?  He was walking in and  out of the  restaurant the entire time. Unless he's a magician with terrible cooking skills there is no way. So the plate sat uneaten on the table and when the bill came he made sure to charge us $20 for the disgusting concoction. We then told him to take the pasta back and take it off the  check. This apparently really ticked him off. (Guess losing  $20 off a $200 bill was just too much for him to bare) so he had the  AUDACITY to come to the table very aggressively and tell me that I completely changed the dish and I can't expect anything. Umm, telling the kitchen to leave out the tiny amount of tomato sauce shouldn't leave me with a soupy mess. I've never seen a MANAGER/OWNER with such little class and tact, but then again the restaurant is located in a dumpy area of Bensonhurst so I guess his personality mirrors the  dumpsters across from the restaurant. Oh and  MAKE SURE if you like eating floating pasta dishes in dirty water you  BRING YOUR OWN WINE  because every bottle they have tastes like a mix of vinegar and grape juice. The owner obviously knows nothing about HOSPITALITY, GASTRONOMY or ENOLOGY.
